President Barack Obama has declared November 2016 as Military Family Month in the United States. In his proclamation, he recognizes the sacrifices made by the families of military personnel and acknowledges their important role in supporting the armed forces. The President highlights the challenges faced by military families, such as long deployments and frequent moves, and emphasizes the need for support and care for these families throughout their service. He mentions the initiatives undertaken by his administration, including the Joining Forces initiative led by First Lady Michelle Obama and Dr. Jill Biden, which aims to provide resources and opportunities for service members, veterans, and their families. The President also applauds the efforts made by businesses and states to facilitate employment and professional licensing for military spouses. He emphasizes the importance of education and STEM opportunities for military children and expresses gratitude for the dedication and sacrifice of military families. President Obama encourages all Americans to honor military families through private actions and public service.